calls for a science that is both more epistemically adequate and socially just, a science that would ask: How are the lives of the most economically and politically vulnerable groups affected by a particular piece of research? Do they have a say in whether and how the research is done? Should empirically reliable systems of indigenous knowledge count as "real science"? Ultimately, Harding argues for a shift from the ideal of a neutral, disinterested science to one that prizes fairness and responsibility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aObjectivity. 0aSciencexPhilosophy. 0aSciencexSocial aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aobjectivity, diversity, scientific research, science, methodology, neutrality, knowledge, information, social justice, epistemology, indigenous, truth, experience, empiricism, reliable, marginalized groups, democracy, fairness, equity, responsibility, anthropology, sociology, politics, nonfiction, theory, political movements, women, gender, poverty, class, developing world, positivism, secularism, inclusion, postcolonialism, sexism, religion, intersectionality, logic, fact, verifiability.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226241531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226241531/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles